Exploratory Data Analysis¶

by Marc Mascaro¶

Introduction¶

This data consists of 426,880 records of used cars for sale on Craigslist. The data was downloaded from Kaggle and can be found at https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/austinreese/craigslist-carstrucks-data.

Notes on data¶

Data types¶

  • we won't do math operations on id column. can change to object.
  • we won't do math on lat / long columns; however, will use later for map so will leave data type as is.

Data issues¶

  • county column has no values and can be dropped.
  • size column has over 70 percent missing values and can be removed.
  • cylinder column has the word "cylinder" for each non-missing entry. this is not an issue per se, however column has over 40% missing values.
  • url columns are not necessary and can be removed.
  • VIN column is not needed and can be removed.
  • description column is not needed and can be removed.
  • posting_data column is not needed and can be removed.
  • price has a minimum of 0 and maximum of 3.7 billion. that seems a bit expensive for a car.

Clean¶

  • drop the following columns

    • url, region_url, image_url, VIN, description, county, size, posting_date

  • change data types

    • id from int to object
    • year from float to int

  • subset data to vehicle prices 100K and below

  • handle missing data
  • create vehicle_age column

def change_dtype(df, cols, type):
    '''
    change_dtype: change data type of columns 
    input: dataframe, list of columns, data type
    output: dataframe with changed column data types
    '''
    for col in cols:
        df[col] = df[col].astype(type)
    return(df)

A couple of functions to assist with countplots¶

In [28]:
# splitJoin function
'''
Sources: (1) https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/python-string-split-and-join-methods-explained-with-examples/
         (2) Udacity review
splitJoin(): split a string, adding a space before an uppercase letter
Input: string
Output: formatted string
'''

def splitJoin(string):
    return ''.join([x if x.islower() else f" {x}" for x in string])
In [29]:
# countplot function
'''
subCountPlot: countplot is called numerous times, so best to have a function to handle.
Input: dataframe, x variable, hue variable, color, color palette, and order x variable.
Output: countplot with formatted axes and title
Source: Udacity review

Expanded function to pass either x or y variable for situations where categorical variable fits better on y-axis
'''

def subCountPlot(df, plt_var, hue_var=None, color=0, palette=None, order=None, xy=None):
    plt.figure(figsize=[14, 8]) # plot figure size
    
    
    if xy == 'x':
        sns.countplot(data = df, x = plt_var, hue = hue_var, color = sns.color_palette()[color], 
                     palette = palette, order = order, edgecolor = 'black')
        plt_var = splitJoin(plt_var).replace('_', ' ') # if there is an underscore, replace with a space
        plt.xlabel(plt_var.title(), weight = 'bold')
        plt.ylabel('Frequency'.title(), weight = 'bold')
    elif xy == 'y':
        sns.countplot(data = df, y = plt_var, hue = hue_var, color = sns.color_palette()[color], 
                     palette = palette, order = order, edgecolor = 'black')
        plt_var = splitJoin(plt_var).replace('_', ' ') # if there is an underscore, replace with a space
        plt.xlabel('Frequency'.title(), weight = 'bold')
        plt.ylabel(plt_var.title(), weight = 'bold')
    
    if hue_var:
        hue_var = splitJoin(hue_var).replace('_', ' ') # same for hue_var, if one is passed in.
    
    # add titles and axis labels
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {plt_var} {'by' if hue_var else ''} {hue_var if hue_var else ''}'''.title(), weight = 'bold')

Univariate exploration¶

Correlation matrix for numeric variables¶

  • are there strong positive or negative correlations among numeric variables?
In [30]:
# numeric variables correlation plot 
plt.figure(figsize = [14, 8])
sns.heatmap(cars_df_clean.corr(), annot = True, fmt = '.3f',
           cmap = 'vlag_r', center = 0)
plt.title('Correlation of numeric variables', weight = 'bold')
plt.show()

There is a postive correlation between

  • year and price - as year increases, price increase
  • vehicle age and odometer - as vehicle age increases, odometer reading increases

There is negative correlations between

  • year and odometer - as year increases, odomoter reading decreases
  • price and odometer - as price decreases, odometer reading increase

# box plots
'''
boxes(x, y, **kwargs): call Seaborn PairGrid to display multiple box plots
Input: dataframe, x variables, y variables, additional arguments
Output: box plots
'''

def boxes (x, y, **kwargs):
    base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.boxplot(x = x, y = y, color = base_color)
